Yes, sorry, it may be easier to just create a version of the code with heavy instrumentation to pinpoint the places it throws. Something as crude as the following could help localize the troublemaker.
        
        try {
             < block of code >
        }
        catch (solver_exception & ex) {
            std::cout << __FILE__ << " " << __LINE << "\n";
            throw ex;
        }

There are some more sophisticated ways: logging the exception stacks in the exception handlers, but 
I last I looked into this it was highly platform dependent for C++ and also really obscure.

Here is an alternative approach.
- You use a solver `sol_store` to store the update the assertions with `add`, `push/pop`.
- But when checking the assertions, you can create a new temporal solver, `sol_tmp`. Then add the assertions in `sol_store` to the solver `sol_tmp`.
     
    ~~~~
      context c;
      sol_sotre(c);
      sol_store.add(e1);
      sol_store.add(e2);
      sol_tmp(c);
      sol_tmp.add(mk_and(sol_sotre.assertions());
     ~~~~

